non-default values provided in userProvidedConfiguration to override whatever was in the JSON

I think this means that you'll still overwrite config file values, if they aren't the defaults. No?
I like the second mechanism you propose, better, I think.
Basically:

Create a config from the file json. This will have 0...all values as null;
Create a config from user. This will have 0...all values as null;
Merge the two configs according to the rule:

if (userProvided.getSomeConfigValue() != null) {
    use(userProvided.getSomeConfigValue());
} else {
    use(configFileProvided.getSomeConfigValue());


As a final step, evaluate the merged config. If any fields are still null, then use a default value.

That is kind of a lot of machinery isn't it (eye-roll) sigh.

I think this means that you'll still overwrite config file values, if they aren't the defaults. No?

Correct. The assumption here is that any non-default values passed via the userProvidedConfiguration will clobber anything that was set via the file. That being said, if we want to respect any non-default settings set via the config file, I can add an extra check in the setters:
public Builder syncMaxRecords(@IntRange(from = 0) int syncMaxRecords) {
    //Only set this value if the current value is default AND the incoming value is NOT default
    if (this.syncMaxRecords == DEFAULT_SYNC_MAX_RECORDS && 
        syncMaxRecords != DEFAULT_SYNC_MAX_RECORDS) {
        this.syncMaxRecords = syncMaxRecords;
    }
    return Builder.this;
}

I think in the end, it comes down to deciding which is more authoritative: the config file or the java object passed in via the constructor.
The drawback of making them nullable is that you need to have that extra step to ensure defaults are set. When I started going that route, there was no clear place for that. I couldn't do it on the build method of the builder, because I actually need the values to remain null. So I would need something (probably in the plugin's configure method) that would set those defaults.
Another thing I just thought of if we want to go the null route, is that I could modify the getters to return their respective defaults if the underlying field is null. I may give that a try.

